    {
      "@id": "faqSection",
      "@type": "FAQPage",
      "name": {"@value": "Semantic Medallion FAQ", "@language": "en"},
      "description": {"@value": "Frequently asked questions about the Semantic Medallion architecture and knowledge graph-powered data catalogs.", "@language": "en"},
      "mainEntity": [
        {"@id": "q1"}, {"@id": "q2"}, {"@id": "q3"}, {"@id": "q4"},
        {"@id": "q5"}, {"@id": "q6"}, {"@id": "q7"}, {"@id": "q8"},
        {"@id": "q9"}, {"@id": "q10"}, {"@id": "q11"}, {"@id": "q12"}
      ],
      "isPartOf": {"@id": "analysis"}
    },

    {
      "@id": "q1", "@type": "Question",
      "text": {"@value": "What is the Semantic Medallion?", "@language": "en"},
      "acceptedAnswer": {"@id": "a1"},
      "isPartOf": {"@id": "faqSection"}
    },
    {
      "@id": "a1", "@type": "Answer",
      "text": {"@value": "The Semantic Medallion is an extension of the traditional Bronze/Silver/Gold data lakehouse architecture where the Gold layer is transformed into a connected knowledge graph rather than isolated clean tables. Relationships are embedded in the data itself, not in external join logic, enabling entity resolution, cross-system queries, and semantic search.", "@language": "en"}
    },

    {
      "@id": "q2", "@type": "Question",
      "text": {"@value": "How does the Bronze layer work in the Semantic Medallion?", "@language": "en"},
      "acceptedAnswer": {"@id": "a2"},
      "isPartOf": {"@id": "faqSection"}
    },
    {
      "@id": "a2", "@type": "Answer",
      "text": {"@value": "The Bronze layer handles standard raw data ingestion via orchestration tools. Data is ingested in its original format with no semantic transformation. DCAT links these raw datasets to their source systems.", "@language": "en"}
    },

    {
      "@id": "q3", "@type": "Question",
      "text": {"@value": "What is the role of IRI minting in the Silver layer?", "@language": "en"},
      "acceptedAnswer": {"@id": "a3"},
      "isPartOf": {"@id": "faqSection"}
    },
    {
      "@id": "a3", "@type": "Answer",
      "text": {"@value": "In the Silver layer, beyond cleaning and typing data, stable IRIs are minted for every entity. These globally unique identifiers replace database auto-increment IDs and GUIDs, creating join keys that work across all systems rather than being scoped to a single database.", "@language": "en"}
    },

    {
      "@id": "q4", "@type": "Question",
      "text": {"@value": "How does the Gold layer transform data into a knowledge graph?", "@language": "en"},
      "acceptedAnswer": {"@id": "a4"},
      "isPartOf": {"@id": "faqSection"}
    },
    {
      "@id": "a4", "@type": "Answer",
      "text": {"@value": "The Gold layer maps Silver DataFrames to a shared ontology using OTTR templates and the maplib Python library, then publishes the result as RDF. Rather than creating separate Parquet/Delta tables requiring manual join logic, the data becomes a connected knowledge graph where relationships are stored as triples — making the data inherently relational.", "@language": "en"}
    },

    {
      "@id": "q5", "@type": "Question",
      "text": {"@value": "Can the DataFrame-to-RDF transformation really be done in four lines of Python?", "@language": "en"},
      "acceptedAnswer": {"@id": "a5"},
      "isPartOf": {"@id": "faqSection"}
    },
    {
      "@id": "a5", "@type": "Answer",
      "text": {"@value": "Yes. The complete Silver-to-Gold transformation uses four lines: (1) load the DataFrame, (2) define an OTTR template mapping columns to ontology properties, (3) apply the template using maplib, and (4) publish the resulting RDF to the Gold layer. The power comes from declarative templates rather than imperative code.", "@language": "en"}
    },

    {
      "@id": "q6", "@type": "Question",
      "text": {"@value": "Why use DCAT instead of a custom catalog schema?", "@language": "en"},
      "acceptedAnswer": {"@id": "a6"},
      "isPartOf": {"@id": "faqSection"}
    },
    {
      "@id": "a6", "@type": "Answer",
      "text": {"@value": "DCAT (Data Catalog Vocabulary) is a W3C standard used by data.gov, the European Data Portal, and thousands of organisations. It provides interoperability with existing catalog ecosystems, rich standardised metadata, a unified graph where the catalog is part of the knowledge graph, and built-in integration with PROV-O for provenance.", "@language": "en"}
    },

    {
      "@id": "q7", "@type": "Question",
      "text": {"@value": "How does the Semantic Medallion handle entity resolution across different data sources?", "@language": "en"},
      "acceptedAnswer": {"@id": "a7"},
      "isPartOf": {"@id": "faqSection"}
    },
    {
      "@id": "a7", "@type": "Answer",
      "text": {"@value": "Entity resolution uses owl:sameAs assertions to link entities appearing in CRM, billing, and external registries. A customer appearing in both the sales system and the billing system is linked via an owl:sameAs triple, creating a unified view. SPARQL queries then navigate all facts about that customer regardless of which source system contributed them.", "@language": "en"}
    },

    {
      "@id": "q8", "@type": "Question",
      "text": {"@value": "How does PROV-O enable data lineage in the Semantic Medallion?", "@language": "en"},
      "acceptedAnswer": {"@id": "a8"},
      "isPartOf": {"@id": "faqSection"}
    },
    {
      "@id": "a8", "@type": "Answer",
      "text": {"@value": "PROV-O expresses data lineage as RDF triples — recording which entities were derived from which sources, which activities generated them, and which agents were responsible. Provenance triples live in the knowledge graph, making lineage queryable using the same SPARQL endpoint as the data itself.", "@language": "en"}
    },

    {
      "@id": "q9", "@type": "Question",
      "text": {"@value": "What was the biggest challenge when building a Semantic Medallion?", "@language": "en"},
      "acceptedAnswer": {"@id": "a9"},
      "isPartOf": {"@id": "faqSection"}
    },
    {
      "@id": "a9", "@type": "Answer",
      "text": {"@value": "The biggest challenge was not the RDF conversion itself, but establishing stable identifiers (IRIs) in the Silver layer. This requires upfront design of IRI naming conventions and careful governance to ensure identifiers remain consistent as new data sources are added.", "@language": "en"}
    },

    {
      "@id": "q10", "@type": "Question",
      "text": {"@value": "How should you approach ontology design for a Semantic Medallion?", "@language": "en"},
      "acceptedAnswer": {"@id": "a10"},
      "isPartOf": {"@id": "faqSection"}
    },
    {
      "@id": "a10", "@type": "Answer",
      "text": {"@value": "Start with the ontology available from your existing data models, then refine incrementally as you understand cross-system relationships better. Do not aim for a perfect ontology upfront — the knowledge graph can evolve as your understanding deepens.", "@language": "en"}
    },

    {
      "@id": "q11", "@type": "Question",
      "text": {"@value": "What is the key difference between a traditional Gold layer and the Semantic Gold layer?", "@language": "en"},
      "acceptedAnswer": {"@id": "a11"},
      "isPartOf": {"@id": "faqSection"}
    },
    {
      "@id": "a11", "@type": "Answer",
      "text": {"@value": "A traditional Gold layer consists of separate Parquet or Delta tables requiring manual join logic in SQL or dbt scripts. The Semantic Gold layer is RDF where relationships are embedded in the data as triples — eliminating table hunting, manual JOINs, and fragile transformation pipelines. The data becomes inherently connected.", "@language": "en"}
    },

    {
      "@id": "q12", "@type": "Question",
      "text": {"@value": "How does the Semantic Medallion reframe the medallion architecture?", "@language": "en"},
      "acceptedAnswer": {"@id": "a12"},
      "isPartOf": {"@id": "faqSection"}
    },
    {
      "@id": "a12", "@type": "Answer",
      "text": {"@value": "The layers become semantic enrichment stages: Bronze provides no semantics (raw data), Silver provides local semantics through stable identifiers (entities become referable across systems), and Gold provides global semantics through a shared vocabulary (entities connected via typed relationships in a knowledge graph). This transforms the medallion from a storage pattern into a semantic enrichment pipeline.", "@language": "en"}
    },

    {
      "@id": "glossarySection",
      "@type": ["DefinedTermSet", "skos:ConceptScheme"],
      "name": {"@value": "Semantic Medallion Glossary", "@language": "en"},
      "description": {"@value": "Key terms and definitions for understanding the Semantic Medallion architecture.", "@language": "en"},
      "hasDefinedTerm": [
        {"@id": "termSemanticMedallion"}, {"@id": "termIRI"}, {"@id": "termDCAT"},
        {"@id": "termPROVO"}, {"@id": "termOTTR"}, {"@id": "termMaplib"},
        {"@id": "termRDF"}, {"@id": "termSPARQL"}, {"@id": "termKnowledgeGraph"},
        {"@id": "termMedallionArchitecture"}
      ],
      "isPartOf": {"@id": "analysis"}
    },

    {
      "@id": "termSemanticMedallion", "@type": ["DefinedTerm", "skos:Concept"],
      "name": {"@value": "Semantic Medallion", "@language": "en"},
      "skos:definition": {"@value": "An architecture pattern extending the Bronze/Silver/Gold medallion with knowledge graph semantics — transforming the Gold layer into connected RDF.", "@language": "en"},
      "skos:inScheme": {"@id": "glossarySection"}
    },
    {
      "@id": "termIRI", "@type": ["DefinedTerm", "skos:Concept"],
      "name": {"@value": "IRI (Internationalized Resource Identifier)", "@language": "en"},
      "skos:definition": {"@value": "A globally unique, stable identifier for an entity — replacing database auto-increment IDs with identifiers that work across all systems.", "@language": "en"},
      "skos:inScheme": {"@id": "glossarySection"}
    },
    {
      "@id": "termDCAT", "@type": ["DefinedTerm", "skos:Concept"],
      "name": {"@value": "DCAT (Data Catalog Vocabulary)", "@language": "en"},
      "skos:definition": {"@value": "A W3C standard vocabulary for describing data catalogs, datasets, distributions, and data services — used by data.gov and the European Data Portal.", "@language": "en"},
      "skos:inScheme": {"@id": "glossarySection"}
    },
    {
      "@id": "termPROVO", "@type": ["DefinedTerm", "skos:Concept"],
      "name": {"@value": "PROV-O (Provenance Ontology)", "@language": "en"},
      "skos:definition": {"@value": "A W3C standard ontology for representing provenance information — enabling data lineage as queryable RDF triples within the knowledge graph.", "@language": "en"},
      "skos:inScheme": {"@id": "glossarySection"}
    },
    {
      "@id": "termOTTR", "@type": ["DefinedTerm", "skos:Concept"],
      "name": {"@value": "OTTR (Reasonable Ontology Templates)", "@language": "en"},
      "skos:definition": {"@value": "A templating language for RDF that maps structured data columns to ontology properties using declarative stOTTR syntax — enabling concise DataFrame-to-RDF transformations.", "@language": "en"},
      "skos:inScheme": {"@id": "glossarySection"}
    },
    {
      "@id": "termMaplib", "@type": ["DefinedTerm", "skos:Concept"],
      "name": {"@value": "maplib", "@language": "en"},
      "skos:definition": {"@value": "A Python library that applies OTTR templates to DataFrames to produce RDF — enabling the complete Silver-to-Gold transformation in as few as four lines of Python.", "@language": "en"},
      "skos:inScheme": {"@id": "glossarySection"}
    },
    {
      "@id": "termRDF", "@type": ["DefinedTerm", "skos:Concept"],
      "name": {"@value": "RDF (Resource Description Framework)", "@language": "en"},
      "skos:definition": {"@value": "The W3C standard for representing linked data as subject-predicate-object triples — the foundational data model of the Semantic Gold layer.", "@language": "en"},
      "skos:inScheme": {"@id": "glossarySection"}
    },
    {
      "@id": "termSPARQL", "@type": ["DefinedTerm", "skos:Concept"],
      "name": {"@value": "SPARQL", "@language": "en"},
      "skos:definition": {"@value": "The W3C standard query language for RDF knowledge graphs — used to navigate entity relationships, trace lineage, and execute cross-system queries in the Semantic Gold layer.", "@language": "en"},
      "skos:inScheme": {"@id": "glossarySection"}
    },
    {
      "@id": "termKnowledgeGraph", "@type": ["DefinedTerm", "skos:Concept"],
      "name": {"@value": "Knowledge Graph", "@language": "en"},
      "skos:definition": {"@value": "A graph-structured data model where entities are connected by typed relationships — enabling navigation, reasoning, and semantic search across unified data.", "@language": "en"},
      "skos:inScheme": {"@id": "glossarySection"}
    },
    {
      "@id": "termMedallionArchitecture", "@type": ["DefinedTerm", "skos:Concept"],
      "name": {"@value": "Medallion Architecture", "@language": "en"},
      "skos:definition": {"@value": "A data lakehouse design pattern with three layers: Bronze (raw ingestion), Silver (cleaned and typed with IRIs), and Gold (semantic RDF knowledge graph).", "@language": "en"},
      "skos:inScheme": {"@id": "glossarySection"}
    },

    {
      "@id": "howtoSection",
      "@type": "HowTo",
      "name": {"@value": "Building a Semantic Medallion Data Catalog", "@language": "en"},
      "description": {"@value": "Step-by-step guide for building a knowledge graph-powered data catalog using the Semantic Medallion architecture.", "@language": "en"},
      "step": [
        {"@id": "step1"}, {"@id": "step2"}, {"@id": "step3"}, {"@id": "step4"},
        {"@id": "step5"}, {"@id": "step6"}, {"@id": "step7"}
      ],
      "isPartOf": {"@id": "analysis"}
    },

    {
      "@id": "step1", "@type": "HowToStep",
      "name": {"@value": "Ingest Raw Data into Bronze", "@language": "en"},
      "description": {"@value": "Set up orchestration tools to ingest raw data from all source systems into the Bronze layer. Preserve original formats without transformation. Link datasets to sources via DCAT.", "@language": "en"},
      "position": 1
    },
    {
      "@id": "step2", "@type": "HowToStep",
      "name": {"@value": "Clean Data and Mint IRIs in Silver", "@language": "en"},
      "description": {"@value": "Clean and type the data in the Silver layer. Replace database auto-increment IDs with stable, globally unique IRIs for every entity. Define a consistent IRI naming scheme using your organisation's domain namespace.", "@language": "en"},
      "position": 2
    },
    {
      "@id": "step3", "@type": "HowToStep",
      "name": {"@value": "Design the Shared Ontology", "@language": "en"},
      "description": {"@value": "Design a shared ontology that maps your business concepts to RDF classes and properties. Start with existing data models. Use standard vocabularies (DCAT, PROV-O, schema.org) where possible. Iterate and refine as understanding deepens.", "@language": "en"},
      "position": 3
    },
    {
      "@id": "step4", "@type": "HowToStep",
      "name": {"@value": "Define OTTR Templates", "@language": "en"},
      "description": {"@value": "Create OTTR templates in stOTTR syntax that map DataFrame columns to ontology properties. Each template defines how a row in your DataFrame becomes a set of RDF triples.", "@language": "en"},
      "position": 4
    },
    {
      "@id": "step5", "@type": "HowToStep",
      "name": {"@value": "Transform to RDF with maplib", "@language": "en"},
      "description": {"@value": "Use the maplib Python library to apply your OTTR templates to the Silver DataFrames. This transformation produces RDF triples in as few as four lines of Python.", "@language": "en"},
      "position": 5
    },
    {
      "@id": "step6", "@type": "HowToStep",
      "name": {"@value": "Publish to Gold as a Knowledge Graph", "@language": "en"},
      "description": {"@value": "Write the resulting RDF to the Gold layer — as Turtle files on a data lake or directly to a triplestore with a SPARQL endpoint. Register the knowledge graph in a DCAT Catalog with a SPARQL endpoint distribution.", "@language": "en"},
      "position": 6
    },
    {
      "@id": "step7", "@type": "HowToStep",
      "name": {"@value": "Query and Validate", "@language": "en"},
      "description": {"@value": "Use SPARQL to validate the knowledge graph: run customer 360 queries to verify entity resolution, lineage queries to trace provenance, and cross-system queries to confirm relationships are correctly modelled. Iterate on the ontology and templates based on results.", "@language": "en"},
      "position": 7
    },

    {
      "@id": "sparqlQueriesSection",
      "@type": "ArticleSection",
      "name": {"@value": "SPARQL Query Examples", "@language": "en"},
      "description": {"@value": "Four SPARQL queries demonstrating the power of a semantic data catalog: customer 360 view, data lineage tracing, cross-system relationship navigation, and ontology inspection.", "@language": "en"},
      "hasPart": [
        {"@id": "customer360Query"}, {"@id": "lineageQuery"},
        {"@id": "crossSystemQuery"}, {"@id": "ontologyQuery"}
      ],
      "isPartOf": {"@id": "analysis"}
    },

    {
      "@id": "customer360Query",
      "@type": "SoftwareSourceCode",
      "name": {"@value": "Customer 360 Query", "@language": "en"},
      "description": {"@value": "Retrieve every fact about customer C-001 from every data source, unified under one identifier. Uses the DESCRIBE form to return all triples about the entity.", "@language": "en"},
      "programmingLanguage": "SPARQL",
      "text": "PREFIX : <http://example.org/ontology#>\nPREFIX schema: <http://schema.org/>\nPREFIX prov: <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#>\nPREFIX dcat: <http://www.w3.org/ns/dcat#>\n\nDESCRIBE :C-001",
      "codeSampleType": "Query",
      "potentialAction": {
        "@type": "SearchAction",
        "target": "https://linkeddata.uriburner.com/sparql?default-graph-uri=&query=PREFIX+%3A+%3Chttp%3A%2F%2Fexample.org%2Fontology%23%3E%0APREFIX+schema%3A+%3Chttp%3A%2F%2Fschema.org%2F%3E%0APREFIX+prov%3A+%3Chttp%3A%2F%2Fwww.w3.org%2Fns%2Fprov%23%3E%0APREFIX+dcat%3A+%3Chttp%3A%2F%2Fwww.w3.org%2Fns%2Fdcat%23%3E%0ADESCRIBE+%3AC-001&format=text%2Fhtml&timeout=30000&run=+Run+Query+"
      },
      "isPartOf": {"@id": "sparqlQueriesSection"}
    },

    {
      "@id": "lineageQuery",
      "@type": "SoftwareSourceCode",
      "name": {"@value": "Data Lineage Query", "@language": "en"},
      "description": {"@value": "Trace which sources contribute to customer records — identifying the provenance path from Gold entities back through Silver to Bronze datasets.", "@language": "en"},
      "programmingLanguage": "SPARQL",
      "text": "PREFIX : <http://example.org/ontology#>\nPREFIX prov: <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#>\nPREFIX dcat: <http://www.w3.org/ns/dcat#>\n\nSELECT ?source ?dataset ?distribution\nWHERE {\n  :C-001 prov:wasDerivedFrom ?source .\n  ?source prov:hadPrimarySource ?dataset .\n  ?dataset dcat:distribution ?distribution .\n}",
      "codeSampleType": "Query",
      "potentialAction": {
        "@type": "SearchAction",
        "target": "https://linkeddata.uriburner.com/sparql?default-graph-uri=&query=PREFIX+%3A+%3Chttp%3A%2F%2Fexample.org%2Fontology%23%3E%0APREFIX+prov%3A+%3Chttp%3A%2F%2Fwww.w3.org%2Fns%2Fprov%23%3E%0APREFIX+dcat%3A+%3Chttp%3A%2F%2Fwww.w3.org%2Fns%2Fdcat%23%3E%0ASELECT+%3Fsource+%3Fdataset+%3Fdistribution+WHERE+%7B+%3AC-001+prov%3AwasDerivedFrom+%3Fsource+.+%3Fsource+prov%3AhadPrimarySource+%3Fdataset+.+%3Fdataset+dcat%3Adistribution+%3Fdistribution+.+%7D&format=text%2Fhtml&timeout=30000&run=+Run+Query+"
      },
      "isPartOf": {"@id": "sparqlQueriesSection"}
    },

    {
      "@id": "crossSystemQuery",
      "@type": "SoftwareSourceCode",
      "name": {"@value": "Cross-System Relationship Query", "@language": "en"},
      "description": {"@value": "Find all customers with open billing issues who also have active contracts — navigating relationships directly across systems without manual joins.", "@language": "en"},
      "programmingLanguage": "SPARQL",
      "text": "PREFIX : <http://example.org/ontology#>\nPREFIX schema: <http://schema.org/>\n\nSELECT ?customer ?name ?billingIssue ?contract\nWHERE {\n  ?customer a schema:Person ;\n            schema:name ?name ;\n            :hasBillingIssue ?billingIssue ;\n            :hasActiveContract ?contract .\n  ?billingIssue schema:status 'Open' .\n  ?contract schema:status 'Active' .\n}",
      "codeSampleType": "Query",
      "potentialAction": {
        "@type": "SearchAction",
        "target": "https://linkeddata.uriburner.com/sparql?default-graph-uri=&query=PREFIX+%3A+%3Chttp%3A%2F%2Fexample.org%2Fontology%23%3E%0APREFIX+schema%3A+%3Chttp%3A%2F%2Fschema.org%2F%3E%0ASELECT+%3Fcustomer+%3Fname+%3FbillingIssue+%3Fcontract+WHERE+%7B+%3Fcustomer+a+schema%3APerson+%3B+schema%3Aname+%3Fname+%3B+%3AhasBillingIssue+%3FbillingIssue+%3B+%3AhasActiveContract+%3Fcontract+.+%3FbillingIssue+schema%3Astatus+%22Open%22+.+%3Fcontract+schema%3Astatus+%22Active%22+.+%7D&format=text%2Fhtml&timeout=30000&run=+Run+Query+"
      },
      "isPartOf": {"@id": "sparqlQueriesSection"}
    },

    {
      "@id": "ontologyQuery",
      "@type": "SoftwareSourceCode",
      "name": {"@value": "Ontology Inspection Query", "@language": "en"},
      "description": {"@value": "Inspect the Semantic Medallion ontology — list all defined classes with their labels and descriptions.", "@language": "en"},
      "programmingLanguage": "SPARQL",
      "text": "PREFIX : <https://moderndata101.substack.com/p/the-semantic-medallion#>\nPREFIX rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#>\n\nSELECT ?class ?label ?comment\nWHERE {\n  ?class a rdfs:Class ;\n         rdfs:label ?label ;\n         rdfs:comment ?comment .\n  FILTER(STRSTARTS(STR(?class), STR(:)))\n}\nORDER BY ?label",
      "codeSampleType": "Query",
      "potentialAction": {
        "@type": "SearchAction",
        "target": "https://linkeddata.uriburner.com/sparql?default-graph-uri=&query=PREFIX+%3A+%3Chttps%3A%2F%2Fmoderndata101.substack.com%2Fp%2Fthe-semantic-medallion%23%3E%0APREFIX+rdfs%3A+%3Chttp%3A%2F%2Fwww.w3.org%2F2000%2F01%2Frdf-schema%23%3E%0ASELECT+%3Fclass+%3Flabel+%3Fcomment+WHERE+%7B+%3Fclass+a+rdfs%3AClass+%3B+rdfs%3Alabel+%3Flabel+%3B+rdfs%3Acomment+%3Fcomment+.+FILTER%28STRSTARTS%28STR%28%3Fclass%29%2C+STR%28%3A%29%29%29+%7D+ORDER+BY+%3Flabel&format=text%2Fhtml&timeout=30000&run=+Run+Query+"
      },
      "isPartOf": {"@id": "sparqlQueriesSection"}
    },

    {
      "@id": "bronzeLayer",
      "@type": "ArticleSection",
      "name": {"@value": "Bronze Layer — Raw Ingestion", "@language": "en"},
      "description": {"@value": "Standard raw data ingestion via orchestration tools. Data is ingested in its original format with no semantic transformation. Linked to raw source datasets via DCAT.", "@language": "en"},
      "isPartOf": {"@id": "analysis"}
    },

    {
      "@id": "silverLayer",
      "@type": "ArticleSection",
      "name": {"@value": "Silver Layer — IRI Minting", "@language": "en"},
      "description": {"@value": "Beyond cleaning and typing, this layer focuses on minting stable IRIs for every entity — creating join keys that work across all systems rather than relying on database auto-increment IDs or GUIDs.", "@language": "en"},
      "isPartOf": {"@id": "analysis"}
    },

    {
      "@id": "goldLayer",
      "@type": "ArticleSection",
      "name": {"@value": "Gold Layer — Semantic RDF", "@language": "en"},
      "description": {"@value": "Silver DataFrames are mapped to a shared ontology using OTTR templates and published as RDF via four lines of Python using maplib. Relationships are in the data, not in join logic.", "@language": "en"},
      "isPartOf": {"@id": "analysis"}
    },

    {
      "@id": "platinumLayer",
      "@type": "ArticleSection",
      "name": {"@value": "Platinum Layer — Semantic Web", "@language": "en"},
      "description": {"@value": "The RDF-based Knowledge Graph is deployed using Linked Data principles — leveraging the power of hyperlinks for entity and relationship naming. This manifests a Semantic Web: a web-scale, decentralised graph where IRIs are dereferenceable and knowledge is globally interconnected.", "@language": "en"},
      "comment": {"@id": "platinumLayerComment"},
      "isPartOf": {"@id": "analysis"}
    },

    {
